<div class="article-headline" id="Headline">PORK, TOMATILLO, AND GREEN CHILE STEW</div>

<div class="article-byline" id="ByLine">BY ELIZABETH NELSON</div>

<div class="article-in-image" id="image1"><img src="images/page022.article001.image1.jpg" class="article-in-image" alt=""/></div>
<div id="separatorLine"> <div class="invisible">empty</div> </div>

<div class="articleImageCredit" id="ImageCredit">PHOTOGRAPHY BY WILLIAM DICKEY</div>
<div class="article-body" id="Body"><p class="no-indent">Makes 8 to 10 servings </p><br/><p class="no-indent">2 tablespoons butter </p><p class="no-indent">1 teaspoon salt </p><p class="no-indent">1 teaspoon cumin </p><p class="no-indent">5 pounds boneless pork shoulder, excess fat trimmed and cut into 1½ inch pieces </p><p class="no-indent">1½ cups chopped onions </p><p class="no-indent">1 cup chopped poblano pepper </p><p class="no-indent">1 tablespoon minced jalapeño pepper</p><p class="no-indent">4 cloves garlic, minced </p><p class="no-indent">1½ cups chicken broth </p><p class="no-indent">1 (16-ounce) jar tomatillo salsa </p><p class="no-indent">1 (15.5-ounce) can hominy, drained and rinsed </p><p class="no-indent">¼ cup chopped fresh cilantro </p><br/><p class="no-indent">1. Preheat oven to 325º. In a large oven-safe Dutch oven, melt butter over medium high-heat. Sprinkle salt and cumin over pork. Working in batches, add pork to pan and brown on all sides, about 5 minutes. Add onions and next 3 ingredients, and cook for 5 minutes or until onion softens. Stir in pork, chicken broth, salsa, and hominy. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">2. Cover and bake for 1 hour and 20 minutes or until pork is tender. Skim fat from the top. Stir in cilantro.</p></div>
